Unless the `jquery.js` file you&#39;re importing has `export` in it, you can&#39;t use `import` to import things from it. (You *can* use `import` to load it though it may not be a good idea, more below.) Native browser support only handles importing from things written as modules.

&gt;     import * as $ from &#39;../node_modules/jquery/dist/jquery.js&#39;;
&gt;     console.log($());
&gt;
&gt; gives me in console
&gt;
&gt; &lt;pre&gt;TypeError: $ is not a function&lt;/pre&gt;

The reason for that is that when you use `* as $` in your `import`, you&#39;re importing the *module namespace object* for the module. The module namespace object is never callable, it&#39;s an object with properties for the exports of the module. You can use `* as x` syntax to import any script, even one that isn&#39;t written to be a module and so doesn&#39;t have `export` anywhere, but all you get is an empty object, because a script not written as a module doesn&#39;t have any exports.

&gt; but if i write in console after this mesage appear :
&gt;
&gt;     console.log($());
&gt;
&gt; it works as expected

That&#39;s because jQuery creates a global `$` using the `window` global. The only reason you couldn&#39;t use that global `$` in your module is that you&#39;ve *shadowed* it by using `$` as the identifier for the module namespace object.

This would probably work:

    import &#39;../node_modules/jquery/dist/jquery.js&#39;;

...because that will load and run the jQuery script, which creates a global. Since that doesn&#39;t declare a module-local identifier with the name `$`, if you use `$` in your module, it uses the *global* `$` that jQuery creates.

But I&#39;m leery of using `import` to load scripts that aren&#39;t designed to be used as modules. Instead, I think I&#39;d just include jQuery using a `script` tag, and then have your module separately using the global `$`.

    &lt;script src=&quot;node_modules/jquery/dist/jquery.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;script src=&quot;js/test.js&quot; type=&quot;module&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

(Or find a module-wrapped version of jQuery; I don&#39;t specifically know of one, but it probably exists.)

